Kowloon's Black Ledger is the sealed record of condemned-debtor transfers made by proto-Kowloon delta settlements to the Spirebound Conclave during the Ash-and-Iron years.
The Black Ledger is parallel to Midgaard's trade ledger: both document the same institutional chain from different ends.
Midgaard's ledger records payment received for transferred subjects; Kowloon's Black Ledger records the delta settlement census entries that were stripped from the public registry before transfer.
The Black Ledger exists as a sealed cistern archive — said to be held in one of the Gloamvault-adjacent undercity chambers accessible from Kowloon's drainage system.
Deltari communities were most heavily represented in the condemned-debtor transfer lists: delta settlement Deltari had the lowest civic standing and the fewest institutional protections at the time of transfer.
The Neon Covenant's founding documents explicitly reference the condemned-debtor period without naming it directly — the "one ledger, one ration code" principle was partly a response to the dual-registry system that had made delta population transfers administratively invisible.
Both Reckoning factions (in Kowloon and Midgaard) seek to open the Black Ledger; both Continuity factions seek to keep it sealed.
The shared institutional guilt creates a perverse solidarity: Kowloon cannot fully prosecute Midgaard's Reckoning case without opening its own Black Ledger, and Midgaard cannot fully prosecute Kowloon's without exposing its own trade ledger entries.
Ash Scriptorium cyclic chains held by the Courier Lantern Office contain independent corroboration of Black Ledger period events — creating outside documentation that persists regardless of whether the primary sealed record is opened.
The Spirebound Conclave's eventual collapse destroyed most evidence on the receiving end; the Black Ledger and Midgaard's trade ledger are among the best surviving records of what was transferred and why.

