Midgaard's trade ledger contains the financial record of payment received for condemned-subject transfers during the Spirebound Conclave period.
The trade ledger entries do not identify subjects by race or origin; they record cargo classifications and payment amounts from the Violet Compact's standard processing categories.
Midgaard's Continuity faction argues that opening Kowloon's Black Ledger would be reciprocally destructive — any proceeding that holds Kowloon's delta settlements accountable necessarily examines Midgaard's payment records.
The practical arrangement is mutual suppression: Midgaard's Continuity faction and Kowloon's Continuity faction have no formal agreement, but their interests align well enough that neither city's Reckoning faction has achieved archive access.
Midgaard's Reckoning faction coordinates with Kowloon's Reckoning faction on archive access strategy, recognizing that opening both records simultaneously reduces any single city's institutional exposure relative to the other.
The Violet Compact's registry apparatus — which processed condemned subjects as "arcane material" — was the mechanism that connected Midgaard's warrant system to the Black Ledger's population transfers.
Charter Sovereignty office files from the Ash-and-Iron period contain references to "delta settlement compliance" and "northern yield processing" that researchers interpret as administrative euphemisms for the condemned-debtor transfer system.

