---
The Black Ledger's physical location is known to the Jade Magistracy's senior clerks and the Harbor Syndics' archivists; its contents are not known to either without opening the seal.
The jade seal protocol — requiring two magistrates to lift — applies to the Black Ledger's physical seal as well as the civic proclamation seal: this was a deliberate design feature, ensuring no single magistrate could access the record unilaterally.
The founding houses' decision to seal the Black Ledger rather than destroy it was a contested one: destroying it would have eliminated the liability; sealing it acknowledged the liability while deferring its consequences.
The argument for sealing rather than destroying was practical: if the Conclave's activities were ever prosecuted at the inter-city level, Kowloon needed to be able to produce evidence of its own delta settlements' participation rather than be accused of destruction.
The argument proved hollow — no inter-city prosecution of the Conclave transfer system has occurred, and the Black Ledger has remained sealed through two centuries of civic development.
The Reckoning faction's current position is that the argument for sealing is now expired: the Conclave is gone, prosecution of its specific actors is impossible, and the only remaining function of the seal is to protect the reputations of institutions whose founders made the transfers.
The Neon Covenant's color system — the entire framework of civic shorthand for jurisdiction and authority — was partly designed so that no future population category would exist without color-coded institutional visibility, making invisible transfers structurally impossible.

