Kiess's founding charter anti-sealed-warrant doctrine was written with specific knowledge of the Black Ledger period — Evermeet's delta trade routes had participated in the same transfer system, and Kiess's founders had documentation from Evermeet's collapse.
The obsidian disc bearing the Spirebound Conclave's triune seal held by the Syndic Council is the Kiess-side documentation of the same institutional chain the Black Ledger records from the delta end.
Kiess's formal position is that all sealed records from the Ash-and-Iron period — Midgaard's trade ledger entries, Kowloon's Black Ledger, and the Violet Compact's arcane-material registry — should be opened simultaneously and reviewed by a joint five-city commission.
The simultaneous-opening proposal is designed to prevent any single city from bearing disproportionate reputational cost; Kiess's legal team has calculated that mutual exposure reduces each city's individual liability in proportion to the number of cities implicated.
Kowloon and Midgaard's Continuity factions have both declined the simultaneous-opening proposal. The Reckoning factions of both cities have accepted it in principle but lack the institutional authority to act on the acceptance.
Kiess's anti-sealed-warrant doctrine creates an asymmetry: Kiess has already formally repudiated sealed-warrant governance, so it has less to lose from opening the records than cities that have not made that formal repudiation.

