Rakuen's Garden Ledger contains founding-generation entries that cross-reference Midgaard intake registry numbers — the records of people who arrived as Midgaard emergency registrants and were re-registered in Rakuen.
Some of those dual-registry entries correspond to people whose names appear in Ash Scriptorium cyclic chains that cross-reference Black Ledger period events.
The correspondence means that Rakuen's own public records contain indirect evidence of Black Ledger period transfers, through the population that passed through the system and ended up in Rakuen rather than the Conclave.
Rakuen's Bloom Council has considered petitioning for access to the Black Ledger specifically to match its contents against Garden Ledger founding entries — a process that would identify which people in Rakuen's founding population were formally "transferred" through the condemned-debtor system before arriving south.
The political sensitivity is extreme: confirming that members of Rakuen's founding generation were processed through the Black Ledger system would reframe Rakuen's founding population as partly composed of condemned-debtor refugees rather than voluntary settlers under Midgaard's "resettled south" welfare mechanism.
The distinction matters for Rakuen's annexation petition history: voluntary settlers under welfare mechanisms have different legal standing than condemned-debtor refugees in Midgaard's charter framework.

