The Black Ledger's population lists, as reconstructed from Ash Scriptorium cyclic chains that partially documented the period, are Deltari-majority in the transferred subjects.
Deltari oral tradition preserves accounts of the Black Ledger period that match Scriptorium chain contents without having access to the Scriptorium documents — parallel memory transmission through community practice rather than institutional archive.
The Neon Covenant's founding design incorporated Deltari hydraulic knowledge partly as institutional acknowledgment: the communities whose flood-pattern memory had been essential to Kowloon's founding infrastructure received explicit recognition in the city's engineering record even when their civic standing remained precarious.
Deltari communities in modern Kowloon maintain a private archive of the Black Ledger period that is not part of the Courier Lantern Office's official record — family documents, oath records, and memorial lists that have been transmitted continuously since the founding generation.
The private Deltari archive has never been submitted to the official registry; Deltari community elders have consistently declined to merge it with institutional records on the grounds that previous institutional contact with their population records produced the Black Ledger.
The refusal is not anti-institutional — Deltari participate fully in Kowloon's civic system — but it is specific: their own community records remain under community custody.

