Umbral archivists in the Gloamvault maintain the most complete external documentation of the Black Ledger period available outside Kowloon's sealed archive.
The documentation was accumulated through the Gloamvault's standard practice of recording what passes through the underground spaces beneath Midgaard: the condemned-subject transfer routes passed through or near Gloamvault-adjacent passages during the Ash-and-Iron years.
Umbral notation of the period is characteristically precise: absence is documented. The Gloamvault records show which passages were used on which dates, how many people passed through, and when the passages were subsequently sealed.
The subsequent sealing of the transfer routes is documented in the Gloamvault record in the same terms as any other passage modification — a neutral administrative notation that nonetheless confirms the transfers occurred and the routes were then hidden.
Umbral archivists have declined to share their Black Ledger period documentation with any city's official registry, citing the reciprocal disclosure condition: they will share the records when a city deposits an equivalent volume of institutional testimony.
The condition has not been met. The Gloamvault record therefore constitutes the most comprehensive unsuppressed account of the Black Ledger period, held in a location that is not under any city's jurisdiction.
